# Symdue License Overview

Symdue uses a dual-license structure to balance open-source freedom with commercial sustainability.

## Runtime: GNU AGPL v3.0

The Symdue runtime — including the Temporal integration, graph executor, storage backend implementations, LLM provider adapters, container management, signal/wait/event runtime, canvas backend, REST/WebSocket API, database models, middleware, and CLI tooling — is licensed under the **GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 or later**.

See [LICENSE-AGPL](LICENSE-AGPL) for the full text.

Files licensed under AGPL v3 carry the SPDX identifier:

```
SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later
```

## Plugin SDK + spec: Apache License 2.0

The NodeType plugin SDK, workflow JSON schemas, and public API specifications — the files in `server/schemas/` (node_type.py, node.py, edge.py, workflow.py, storage.py, event.py, signal.py, run.py, llm_config.py) and any future SDK / spec additions — are licensed under the **Apache License 2.0**.

This means custom NodeTypes built against the plugin SDK are **separate works** under AGPL doctrine. NodeType authors may license their NodeType code however they wish, including proprietary licensing.

See [LICENSE-APACHE](LICENSE-APACHE) for the full text.

Files licensed under Apache 2.0 carry the SPDX identifier:

```
SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0
```

## Demo content: Apache License 2.0

Example workflows, kits, and starter templates in `demos/` are Apache 2.0 so users can copy, modify, and integrate freely.

## Legal precedent for the split

The "permissive API + restrictive core" pattern has 25+ years of legal precedent:

- **PostgreSQL** — PostgreSQL License (BSD-style) core; same license on extension API headers; proprietary extensions (pgvector, TimescaleDB, Citus) distribute under various licenses
- **MySQL** — GPL v2 core; **LGPL** connector libraries explicitly chosen so proprietary applications can call MySQL via connectors. See the [MySQL FOSS License Exception](https://www.mysql.com/about/legal/licensing/foss-exception/)
- **Linux kernel** — GPL v2 core; explicit `EXPORT_SYMBOL` vs `EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL` boundary marking. NVIDIA's proprietary kernel modules use this pattern
- **WordPress** — GPL v2 core; proprietary themes and plugins are widely accepted

Symdue's dual-license structure follows this established pattern: the runtime is "viral" (AGPL v3); the SDK is permissive (Apache 2.0) so plugin authors retain full freedom over their NodeType code.

## Why this split

To keep the runtime substrate genuinely open and self-hostable while preventing cloud hyperscalers from forking Symdue and reselling it as a competing managed service. Same model as Grafana (AGPL Grafana + permissive plugin API) and MongoDB (now SSPL but originally AGPL).

## Commercial license

Specific use cases that need to escape AGPL obligations on the runtime — such as embedding Symdue code directly in a closed-source commercial product, operating Symdue as a hyperscaler-class managed service, or shipping proprietary modifications to the AGPL'd runtime — are available under a separate commercial license.

See [COMMERCIAL_LICENSE.md](COMMERCIAL_LICENSE.md) for terms and contact.

## Contributor License Agreement

Contributions to AGPL'd code (the runtime) require signing the [CLA](CLA.md) so we can offer commercial licenses on top of the AGPL'd codebase. Contributions to the Apache 2.0 SDK and demo content can be made under the standard Apache 2.0 license terms.

See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for the contribution flow.

## Public commitment

We commit to keeping the runtime AGPL v3 forever and the plugin SDK + spec Apache 2.0 forever. We will not relicense to a more restrictive license. We will not move features that are currently OSS into a paid-only tier. See [PRICING_PHILOSOPHY.md](PRICING_PHILOSOPHY.md) for the full set of public commitments.

---

## Quick reference: which license applies to my use case?

| Your situation | License obligation |
|---|---|
| Self-hosting Symdue internally for your team | None — internal use is unrestricted |
| Authoring workflows on Symdue | None — workflows are user content, not derivative works |
| Building custom NodeTypes against the Apache 2.0 SDK | None — your NodeType is a separate work; license it however you want |
| Hosting unmodified Symdue for paying clients | Light — display "Source: github.com/vinodydev/symdue_oss" notice in your deployed UI |
| Modifying the Symdue runtime AND making it network-accessible to third parties | AGPL: release modification source, OR purchase a commercial license |
| Embedding Symdue runtime code directly in a closed-source commercial product | AGPL: release product source, OR purchase a commercial license |
| Operating Symdue as a hyperscaler-class managed service for third parties | AGPL: release managed-service source, OR purchase a commercial license |
| You are Symdue (the copyright owner) hosting Symdue Cloud | None — owners are not bound by their own license |

